1. Python

x = 10

if x > 0:
    print("Positive")
else:
    print("Non-positive")


No parentheses around conditions.

Indentation defines blocks.

No semicolons.

2. PHP

$x = 10;

if ($x > 0) {
    echo "Positive";
} else {
    echo "Non-positive";
}


Uses $ for variables.

Curly braces define blocks.

Semicolons required.

3. MATLAB

x = 10;

if x > 0
    disp('Positive')
else
    disp('Non-positive')
end


No parentheses needed (but can be used).

Uses end to close the block.

disp() for output.

int x = 10;

if (x > 0) {
    System.out.println("Positive");
} else {
    System.out.println("Non-positive");
}


Strongly typed.

Semicolons and braces required.

System.out.println for output.

5. C#

int x = 10;

if (x > 0) {
    Console.WriteLine("Positive");
} else {
    Console.WriteLine("Non-positive");
}


Very similar to Java.

Uses Console.WriteLine.

6. C++

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int x = 10;

if (x > 0) {
    cout << "Positive" << endl;
} else {
    cout << "Non-positive" << endl;
}
